16/*======================================*



17 * SimStruct Get and Set Access methods *



18 *======================================*/



19



20/*-------------------------------- S->modelName -----------------------------*/



21



22/*



23 * ModelName - This is the name of the S-function. When the SimStruct



24 *   is being used with the Real-Time Workshop, then the "root" SimStruct



25 *   model name corresponds to the name of the Simulink model.



26 */



27



28#define _ssSetModelName(S, name) \



29          (S)->modelName = (name)



30#if !SS_SFCN



31#define ssSetModelName(S,name) _ssSetModelName(S,name)



32#else



33#define ssSetModelName(S,name) ssSetModelName_cannot_be_used_in_SFunctions



34#endif



35



36/*-------------------------------- S->path ----------------------------------*/



37/*



38 * Path - This is the full path to the S-function. When the SimStruct



39 *   is being used with the Real-Time Workshop, then the "root" SimStruct



40 *   path corresponds to the name of the Simulink model.



41 */



42



43#define _ssSetPath(S, pathPtr) \



44          (S)->path = (pathPtr)



45#if !SS_SFCN



46#define ssSetPath(S,pathPtr) _ssSetPath(S,pathPtr)



47#else



48#define ssSetPath(S,pathPtr) ssSetPath_cannot_be_used_in_SFunctions



49#endif



50



51/*-------------------------------- S->parent --------------------------------*/



52/*



53 * ParentSS - There is one SimStruct for each S-function in your model.



54 *   There is also a SimStruct for the model itself. The SimStruct's are



55 *   arranged as a tree with the model SimStruct as the root. The ParentSS



56 *   field is used to get at the model SimStruct. User written S-functions



57 *   should not use the ssGetParentSS macro directly.



58 */



59



60#define _ssSetParentSS(S,parentSS) \



61          (S)->parent = (parentSS)



62#if !SS_SFCN



63#define ssSetParentSS(S,parentSS) _ssSetParentSS(S,parentSS)



64#else



65#define ssSetParentSS(S,parentSS) ssSetParentSS_cannot_be_used_in_SFunctions



66#endif



67



68/*-------------------------------- S->root ----------------------------------*/



69/*



70 * RootSS - This is the "root" SimStruct corresponding to the Simulink



71 *   model.



72 */



73



74#define _ssSetRootSS(S,rootSS) \



75          (S)->root = (rootSS)



76#if !SS_SFCN



77#define ssSetRootSS(S,rootSS) _ssSetRootSS(S,rootSS)



78#else



79#define ssSetRootSS(S,rootSS) ssSetRootSS_cannot_be_used_in_SFunctions



80#endif



81



82



83/*-------------------------------- S->errorStatus ---------------------------*/



84



85/* ErrorStatus - For improved performance and error handling, your S-function



86 *   should do:



87 *      ssSetErrorStatus(S, "error message");



88 *      return;



89 *   as opposed to calling mexErrMsgTxt.



90 *



91 *   Be careful when using ssSetErrorStatus in your S-function. Sometimes you



92 *   may wish to use sprintf to format the message. In this case, you



93 *   need to allocate memory for the message as opposed to using the stack.



94 *   macros _ss[SG]et_slErrMsg and _ssIsErrorStatusAslErrMsg



95 *   are intended for internal use only



96 */



97



98



99



100#define _ssGetErrorStatus(S) \



101       ( ssGetRootSS(S)->mdlInfo->mdlFlags.errorStatusIsMsg == 1U ? \



102       NULL : ssGetRootSS(S)->errorStatus.str )



103#define _ssGet_slErrMsg(S) \



104       ( ssGetRootSS(S)->mdlInfo->mdlFlags.errorStatusIsMsg == 0U ? \



105       NULL : ssGetRootSS(S)->errorStatus.msg )



106#define _ssSet_slErrMsg(S, msg_arg) \



107        { ssGetRootSS(S)->mdlInfo->mdlFlags.errorStatusIsMsg = 1U; \



108        ssGetRootSS(S)->errorStatus.msg = (msg_arg); }



109#define _ssIsErrorStatusAslErrMsg(S) \



110        ( ssGetRootSS(S)->mdlInfo->mdlFlags.errorStatusIsMsg == 1U )



111



112#define _ssReportDiagnosticAsWarning(S, diag)                                  \



113    _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)((S), GEN_FCN_REPORT_DIAGNOSTIC_AS_WARNING, \



114                                    0, diag) _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd



115



116#define _ssDiscardDiagnostic(S, diag)                                          \



117    _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)((S), GEN_FCN_DISCARD_DIAGNOSTIC,           \



118                                    0, diag) _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd



119



120#define _ssLongJmp(S, buffer)                                  \



121    _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)((S), GEN_FCN_LONGJMP, \



122                                    0, buffer) _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd



123



124#define SS_ERROR_STATUS_BUFFER_SIZE 1024



125



126#define _ssCopyErrorStatusToBuffer(S, string, size) \



127      { (void)memcpy(ssGetRootSS(S)->mdlInfo->errorStatusBuffer, (string), ((size) > SS_ERROR_STATUS_BUFFER_SIZE-1)? (SS_ERROR_STATUS_BUFFER_SIZE-1) : (size) ); \



128      ssSetErrorStatus(S, ssGetRootSS(S)->mdlInfo->errorStatusBuffer); }

131/* SizesPtr - This is an integer pointer of length SIZES_LENGTH. The



132 *   fields in the sizes pointers are defined in the _ssSizes structure



133 *   (above).



134 */



135#define ssGetSizesPtr(S) \



136          ((int_T *)&(S)->sizes)                          /*   (int_T *)     */

139/* NumTotalStates - This is the number of continuous plus discrete states



140 *   within your S-function. The root SimStruct contains the number of



141 *   continuous plus discrete states within the model itself (including all



142 *   blocks and S-functions).



143 */



144#if SS_SFCN_LEVEL_1 || !SS_SFCN



145# define ssGetNumTotalStates(S) \



146          (ssGetNumContStates(S) + ssGetNumDiscStates(S)) /*   (int_T)       */



147#endif

151 * S-function block.

153#if !SS_SFCN_LEVEL_1



154

156             (S)->portInfo.outputs = (ptr)



157# define ssGetPortInfoForOutputs(S) \



158             (S)->portInfo.outputs



159#endif

163 * S-function block.



164 */



165#if !SS_SFCN_LEVEL_1



166



167



168# define ssSetPortInfoForInputs(S,ptr) \



169             (S)->portInfo.inputs = (ptr)



170# define ssGetPortInfoForInputs(S) \



171             (S)->portInfo.inputs



172#endif

298/* Checksum fields - The checksum fields are primarily used by the root



299 *   SimStruct to maintain consistency between Simulink external mode and



300 *   the code generated from the Real-Time Workshop. In general, user



301 *   written S-function should not use this field.



302 */



303#define ssGetChecksums(S) (S)->sizes.checksums



304



305#define ssSetChecksumVal(S,idx,val)  \



306          (S)->sizes.checksums[idx] = (val)



307#define ssGetChecksumVal(S,idx)  \



308          (S)->sizes.checksums[idx]



309



310#define ssGetChecksum0(S) \



311          (S)->sizes.checksums[0]                         /*   (uint32_T)    */



312#define ssSetChecksum0(S,val) \



313          (S)->sizes.checksums[0] = (val)



314



315#define ssGetChecksum1(S) \



316          (S)->sizes.checksums[1]                         /*   (uint32_T)    */



317#define ssSetChecksum1(S,val) \



318          (S)->sizes.checksums[1] = (val)



319



320#define ssGetChecksum2(S) \



321          (S)->sizes.checksums[2]                         /*   (uint32_T)    */



322#define ssSetChecksum2(S,val) \



323          (S)->sizes.checksums[2] = (val)



324



325#define ssGetChecksum3(S) \



326          (S)->sizes.checksums[3]                         /*   (uint32_T)    */



327#define ssSetChecksum3(S,val) \



328          (S)->sizes.checksums[3] = (val)

330/* NumSFunctions - This field is used by the root SimStruct to keep track



331 *   of the number of child SimStruct's corresponding to S-function blocks.



332 *   This field should not be used by S-function blocks (i.e. should be 0).



333 */



334#define ssGetNumSFunctions(S) \



335          (S)->sizes.numSFunctions                        /*   (int_T)       */



336#define ssSetNumSFunctions(S,nSFunctions) \



337          (S)->sizes.numSFunctions = (nSFunctions)



338



339/* NumBlocks - This field is used by the root SimStruct to keep track of



340 *   the number of non-virtual blocks within the model. This field should



341 *   not be used by S-function blocks (i.e. should be 0).



342 */



343#define ssGetNumBlocks(S) \



344          (S)->sizes.numBlocks                            /*   (int_T)       */



345#define ssSetNumBlocks(S,nBlocks) \



346          (S)->sizes.numBlocks = (nBlocks)



347



348/* Version - This field should not be used by S-function blocks directly.



349 *   The the simulink.c include file at the bottom of your S-function block



350 *   uses this field. It is also used by root SimStruct for versioning.



351 */



352#define ssGetVersion(S) \



353          (S)->sizes.simStructVer                         /*   (int_T)       */



354#define ssSetVersion(S,ver) \



355          (S)->sizes.simStructVer = (int32_T) (ver)



356



357#define ssGetSFcnLevel(S) \



358          ((S)->sizes.simStructVer == (int32_T) SIMSTRUCT_VERSION_LEVEL2? 2: 1)



359

499/*



500 * Query to see if rapid accelerator is active



501 * Note that rapid accelerator simulation can have



502 * simulation mode != rapid hence we need this query



503 */



504#define ssSetIsRapidAcceleratorActive(S,boolVal)                        \



505    ((!ssGetParentSS(S)) ?                                              \



506     ((S)->sizes.flags.isRapidAcceleratorActive = (boolVal) ? 1U : 0U) : \



507     0)

509/*



510 * Query to see if the simstruc is in VM Simulations



511 * boolean_T



512 */



513#define ssGetIsVmSimulationCompile(S)                                          \



514    ((((S)->mdlInfo->genericFcn == NULL)                                       \



515          ? 0                                                                  \



516          : ((*(S)->mdlInfo->genericFcn)((S), GEN_FCN_VM_SIMULATION_COMPILE,   \



517                                         0, (void*)NULL))) == 1)



518/*



519 * Query about the VM Simulations compliance



520 */



521/*  val is of type (unsigned int: 3) */



522#define ssSetVmSimulationsCompliance(S, val)                       \



523    ((S)->sizes.flags.vmSimulationsCompliance = (val))



524



525/*  returns (unsigned int: 3) */



526#define ssGetVmSimulationsCompliance(S)                                \



527    ((S)->sizes.flags.vmSimulationsCompliance)

570/***********************************



571 * Input Port Number of Dimensions *



572 ***********************************/



573



574



575# define _ssSetInputPortNumDimensions(S,port,val) \



576{\



577    (S)->portInfo.inputs[(port)].numDims = (val);\



578    if(val == 1) { \



579        (S)->portInfo.inputs[(port)].dims = \



580                        &((S)->portInfo.inputs[(port)].width);\



581    }\



582}



583



584



585/* Do not make a copy. S-function port dimension = Ptr. */



586# define _ssSetInputPortDimensionsPtr(S,port,ptr) \



587{\



588   (S)->portInfo.inputs[(port)].dims = (ptr);\



589}

600                     nn*sizeof(int_T)); \

648/* InputDimsConstraint - For each input port of your S-function block, this is the

660 /* InputPortSignalPtrs - This is the pointers to the signal vector for each



661  *    input port. This is the default method for accessing the S-Function's



662  *    input signals. It is a *bad* error to use this macro if the S-Function



663  *    specifies ssSetInputPortRequiredContiguous as true. In that case, use



664  *    ssGetInputPortSignal().



665  *



666  *    The following code demonstrates the use of ssGetInputPortSignalPtrs() :



667  *



668  *       nInputPorts = ssGetNumInputPorts(S);



669  *       for (i = 0; i < nInputPorts; i++) {



670  *         InputPtrsType u  = ssGetInputPortSignalPtrs(S,i);



671  *         int_T         nu = ssGetInputPortWidth(S,i);



672  *         for (j = 0; j < nu; j++) {



673  *           UseInputInSomeFunction(*u[i]);



674  *         }



675  *       }



676  *



677  *    If you know that the input's are always real_T's signals, then the



678  *    ssGetInputPortSignalPtrs line in the above code snippet would be:



679  *



680  *         InputRealPtrsType u = ssGetInputPortRealSignalPtrs(S,i);



681  *



682  */



683



684# define _ssSetInputPortSignalPtrs(S,ip,ptr) \



685    (S)->portInfo.inputs[(ip)].signal.ptrs = (ptr)



686# if !SS_SFCN



687#   define ssSetInputPortSignalPtrs(S,ip,ptr) \



688      _ssSetInputPortSignalPtrs(S,ip,ptr)



689# else



690#   define ssSetInputPortSignalPtrs(S,ip,ptr) \



691      ssSetInputPortSignalPtrs_cannot_be_used_in_SFunctions



692# endif



693



694



695 /* InputPortSignal: This macro returns the address of the signal on the



696  *    specified input port of the S-Function. In order to use this macro for



697  *    accessing the input port signal you need to set the attribute



698  *    ssSetInputPortRequiredContiguous to true. If not, this macro returns an



699  *    invalid pointer.



700  *



701  *    The following code demonstrates the use of ssGetInputPortSignal() :



702  *



703  *       nInputPorts = ssGetNumInputPorts(S);



704  *       for (i = 0; i < nInputPorts; i++) {



705  *           int_T nu = ssGetInputPortWidth(S,i);



706  *



707  *           if ( ssGetInputPortRequiredContiguous(S,i) ) {



708  *



709  *               const void *u = ssGetInputPortSignal(S,i);



710  *               UseInputVectorInSomeFunction(u, nu);



711  *



712  *           } else {



713  *



714  *               InputPtrsType u  = ssGetInputPortSignalPtrs(S,i);



715  *               for (j = 0; j < nu; j++) {



716  *                   UseInputInSomeFunction(*u[j]);



717  *               }



718  *           }



719  *       }



720  *



721  *    If you know that the input's are always real_T's signals, then the



722  *    ssGetInputPortSignal line in the above code snippet would be:



723  *



724  *         const real_T *u = ssGetInputPortRealSignal(S,i);



725  *



726  */



727



728# define _ssSetInputPortSignal(S,ip,ptr) \



729          (S)->portInfo.inputs[(ip)].signal.vect = (ptr)



730# if !SS_SFCN



731#   define ssSetInputPortSignal(S,ip,ptr) \



732          _ssSetInputPortSignal(S,ip,ptr)



733# else



734#   define ssSetInputPortSignal(S,ip,ptr) \



735          ssSetInputPortSignal_cannot_be_used_in_SFunctions



736# endif



737

803/* InputPortOptimizeInIR - This macro allows S-Functions that use the code



804 * generation intermediate representation (CGIR) to generate code, to enable



805 * optimizations on for the input port that would otherwise be disabled by



806 * default. For example, the macro should be used if a S-Function set its



807 * input port conservatively as global, because it is accessed in both the



808 * output and the update function. It is possible for CGIR to safely optimize



809 * the port signal if output and update get combined.



810 */



811# define ssGetInputPortOptimizeInIR(S,port) \



812    ( (S)->portInfo.inputs[(port)].attributes.optimizeInIR )



813# define ssSetInputPortOptimizeInIR(S,port,val) \



814    ( (S)->portInfo.inputs[(port)].attributes.optimizeInIR = (val) )

819  *   over-writable, then one of the "untest-pointed" output ports of this



820  *   S-Function might reuse the same buffer as the input port! If this happens,



821  *   then after compilation, the following macro returns the index of the



822  *   output port that reuses the specified input port's buffer. If none of the



823  *   S-Function's output ports reuse this input port buffer, then this macro



824  *   returns INVALID_PORT_IDX ( = -1).



825  */



826

828          (S)->portInfo.inputs[(port)].bufferDstPort = (val)

834            ssSetInputPortBufferDstPort_cannot_be_used_in_SFunctions



835# endif

969 /* OutputPortConstOutputExprInRTW - Specify that the output signal is a constant



970  * expression in RTW (versus a statement).  This allows a downstream block



971  * to fold the expression into its calculation no matter how many destinations



972  * the block has.  Note that Simulink may not honor this setting, in which case



973  * the block must produce a statement.



974  */



975# define ssGetOutputPortConstOutputExprInRTW(S,port) \



976   ((S)->portInfo.outputs[(port)].attributes.constOutputExprInRTW == 1U)



977# define ssSetOutputPortConstOutputExprInRTW(S,port,val) \



978   ((S)->portInfo.outputs[(port)].attributes.constOutputExprInRTW = (val) ? \



979   ((S)->portInfo.outputs[(port)].attributes.trivialOutputExprInRTW = \



980    (S)->portInfo.outputs[(port)].attributes.outputExprInRTW = 1U) : 0U)



981



982



983 /* OutputPortTrivialOutputExprInRTW - Specify that the output signal is a trivial



984  * expression in RTW (versus a statement).  This allows a downstream block



985  * to fold the expression into its calculation no matter how many destinations



986  * the block has.  Note that Simulink may not honor this setting, in which case



987  * the block must produce a statement.



988  */



989# define ssGetOutputPortTrivialOutputExprInRTW(S,port) \



990   ((S)->portInfo.outputs[(port)].attributes.trivialOutputExprInRTW == 1U)



991# define ssSetOutputPortTrivialOutputExprInRTW(S,port,val) \



992   ((S)->portInfo.outputs[(port)].attributes.trivialOutputExprInRTW = (val) ? \



993   ((S)->portInfo.outputs[(port)].attributes.outputExprInRTW = 1U) : \



994   ((S)->portInfo.outputs[(port)].attributes.constOutputExprInRTW = 0U))

1242# define _ssCacheSFcnParamValueAttribs(pName, dtId, nDims, dimsPtr, cplx) \



1243     ssParamRec locPI; \



1244     locPI.name             = pName; \

1251     locPI.nDlgParamIndices = 0; \

1257   { \

1260GEN_FCN_CHECK_SFCN_PARAM_VALUE_ATTRIBS, pIdx, &locPI) \



1261      _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd) return; \

1648/*======================================================================*



1649 * BUS support for S-Functions



1650 *======================================================================*/



1651



1652/*



1653 * APIS for bus support via bus expansion. In this case,



1654 * the s-function block is expanded under the hood into an individual



1655 * s-function for each signal in the bus and then the outputs re-bused



1656 * to output a bus.



1657 *



1658 * Need to set_param(gcb, 'EnableBusSupport', 'on') for the S-Function block



1659 *



1660 * 1) ssSetBusPropagationSupported(S, true)



1661 *    This indicates that bus expansion is desired.



1662 *



1663 * 2) ssSetBusSourcePort(S, portNumber)



1664 *    This indicates that the bus coming into port number (0-based) of the



1665 *    block will supply the structure of the outgoing bus. This bus is also



1666 *    used for getting signal names, signal propagation etc. It is the



1667 *    defining bus for this block.



1668 *    Example: Say for the switch block, this would be set to 0.



1669 *



1670 * 3) ssSetBusInputPorts(S, int number, int* numbers)



1671 *    This indicates the ports of the blocks that accept buses. The bus



1672 *    expansion routine then checks to verify that the incoming buses at these



1673 *    inports are identical in terms of signal names and compiled attributes



1674 *    for successful expansion.



1675 *    Example: For the switch block this is [0 2], so "number" is set to 2



1676 *             and "numbers" is an array of ints of length 2 with values



1677 *             numbers[0] = 0; numbers[1] = 2;



1678 */



1679#define ssSetBusPropagationSupported(S, value)\



1680{    boolean_T tmp = value;\



1681 _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)((S),GEN_FCN_SET_BUS_PROPAGATION, 0, &tmp)\



1682 _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd;\



1683}



1684



1685#define ssSetBusSourcePort(S, port)\



1686{    int tmp = port;\



1687 _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)((S),GEN_FCN_SET_BUS_SOURCE_PORT, 0, &tmp)\



1688 _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd;\



1689}



1690



1691#define ssSetBusInputPorts(S, numInports, value)\



1692 _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)((S),GEN_FCN_SET_BUS_INPORTS, numInports, value)\



1693 _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd



1694



1695/*



1696 * APIS for bus support via bus objects. In this case, the s-function outputs



1697 * a bus as defined by a bus object (which can be a parameter). The output



1698 * function should implement the bus output consistent with the bus object.



1699 *



1700 * Need to set_param(gcb, 'EnableBusSupport', 'on') for the S-Function block



1701 *



1702 * 1)  ssSetBusOutputObjectName(S, int_T portNumber, char* busName)



1703 *     This specifies the bus object that defines the bus coming out of the



1704 *     s-function block at output number (0-based) of the block.



1705 *



1706 * 2)  ssSetBusInputAsStruct(S, int_T portNumber, boolean_T val)



1707 *     This specifies if the input bus as specified by the bus object should



1708 *     be converted to non-virtual if necessary. By setting it to true, an auto-



1709 *     conversion block is inserted behind the scenes to convert a virtual



1710 *     bus input to a non-virtual bus



1711 *



1712 * 3)  ssSetBusOutputAsStruct(S, int_T portNumber, boolean_T val)



1713 *     This specifies if the output bus as specified by the bus object should



1714 *     emerge as a structure (non-virtual) or a virtual bus. By setting it to false,



1715 *     a Signal Conversion block is automatically inserted behind the scenes to



1716 *     output a virtual bus.



1717 *



1718 *     --------------------------------------------------------------------------



1719 *     The next set of macros can be used to obtain information for a specific element



1720 *     of a bus object given the data type index of the bus object and the appropriate



1721 *     bus element index within the bus object. The data type index of the bus object



1722 *     is the index returned by Simulink when the bus object was registered in



1723 *     mdlInitializeSizes() (using ssRegisterTypeFromParameter() for example)



1724 *     --------------------------------------------------------------------------



1725 *



1726 * 4)  ssGetNumBusElements(S, int_T busTypeID)



1727 *     Get the number of bus elements in the specified bus object. The bus data type



1728 *     is passed in as the second argument.



1729 *



1730 * 5)  ssGetBusElementOffset(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



1731 *     Obtain the offset in bytes (int_T) from the start of the bus data type to



1732 *     the specified bus element. The bus data type is passed in as the second



1733 *     argument and the bus element index (zero based index) is passed in as the



1734 *     third argument.



1735 *



1736 * 6)  ssGetBusElementDataType(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



1737 *     Obtain the data type index (int_T) for the specified bus element. The bus data



1738 *     type is passed in as the second argument and the bus element index (zero based



1739 *     index) is passed in as the third argument.



1740 *



1741 * 7)  ssGetBusElementComplexSignal(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



1742 *     Obtain the complexity (CSignal_T) of the specified bus element. The bus



1743 *     data type is passed in as the second argument and the bus element index (zero



1744 *     based index) is passed in as the third argument.



1745 *



1746 * 8)  ssGetBusElementNumDimensions(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



1747 *     Obtain the number of signal dimensions (int_T) for the specified bus element.



1748 *     The bus data type is passed in as the second argument and the bus element index



1749 *     (zero based index) is passed in as the third argument.



1750 *



1751 * 9)  ssGetBusElementDimensions(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



1752 *     Obtain the dimensions (const int_T*) for the specified bus element. Use in combination



1753 *     with ssGetBusElementNumDimensions() above to iterate over the integer array



1754 *     returned by this macro. The bus data type is passed in as the second argument



1755 *     and the bus element index (zero based index) is passed in as the third argument.



1756 *



1757 * 10) ssGetBusElementDimensionsMode(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



1758 *     Obtain the dimensions mode (DimensionsMode_T) for the specified bus element.



1759 *     The bus data type is passed in as the second argument and the bus element index



1760 *     (zero based index) is passed in as the third argument.



1761 *



1762 * 11) ssGetBusElementName(S, int_T busTypeId, int_T elemIdx)



1763 *     Get the name (const char*) of the specified bus element. The bus data type is passed



1764 *     in as the second argument and the bus element index (zero based index) is



1765 *     passed in as the third argument.



1766 *



1767 * 12) ssIsDataTypeABus(S, int_T typeID)



1768 *     Determine if the data type ID passed in is a bus signal. A Boolean_T value is



1769 *     returned.



1770 *



1771 * 13) ssGetBusElementMin(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



1772 *     Obtain the minimum (real_T) for the specified bus element.



1773 *     The bus data type is passed in as the second argument and the bus element index



1774 *     (zero based index) is passed in as the third argument.



1775 *



1776 * 14) ssGetBusElementMax(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



1777 *     Obtain the maximum (real_T) for the specified bus element.



1778 *     The bus data type is passed in as the second argument and the bus element index



1779 *     (zero based index) is passed in as the third argument.



1780 */



1781



1782#if SS_SL_INTERNAL || SS_SFCN_FOR_SIM



1783/* Use of ssSetBusObjectName is not recommended. Please use ssSetBusOutputObjectName instead. */



1784#define ssSetBusObjectName(S, pIdx, name) \



1785 (ssSetBusOutputObjectName((S), (pIdx), (name)))



1786



1787#define ssGetBusElementDimensionsMode(S, busTypeID, elemIdx) \



1788 (dtaGetDataTypeElementDimensionsMode(ssGetDataTypeAccess(S), ssGetPath(S), (busTypeID), (elemIdx)))

3288 *   is then your responsibility to fill in correct values for *pr, *ir, *jc.



3289 *   The values for *ir and *jc should be initialized in function mdlJacobianIrJc.

3385/* SupportRunTimeModelAPI - Runtime model API refers to the model function with



3386'outputs', 'derivs' and 'update' command. If the S-function block writes to



3387any persistent memory during mdlOutputs function, e.g., either dWork or a



3388persistent variable, it is likely that these block may need to set this



3389flag to false.



3390



3391Similarly, if the S-function block writes to any persistent memory other than dX



3392in the mdlDerivatives, or if the S-function block writes to any persistent memory



3393other than the discrete states in mdlUpdate, it is likely that this flag needs



3394to be set to false.



3395



3396The default value for the flag is true.



3397 */



3398#define ssSetSupportRunTimeModelAPI(S, arg)\

3400    _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)((S), GEN_FCN_SET_SUPPORT_RUNTIME_MODEL_API,arg, NULL)\



3401        _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd;\



3402}

3805/* DWorkOptimizeInIR - This macro allows S-Functions that use the code



3806 * generation intermediate representation (CGIR) to generate code, to enable



3807 * optimizations that would otherwise be disabled by default. For example,



3808 * the macro should be used if a S-Function set its DWork conservatively as



3809 * global, because it is accessed in both the



3810 * output and the update function. It is possible for CGIR to safely optimize



3811 * the DWork if output and update get combined.



3812 */



3813#define ssGetDWorkOptimizeInIR(S,index) \



3814    ((S)->work.dWorkAux[(index)].flags.optimizeInIR)



3815#define ssSetDWorkOptimizeInIR(S,index,val) \



3816    (S)->work.dWorkAux[(index)].flags.optimizeInIR = val



3817

6173typedef struct {



6174    void* data;



6175    int_T dtId;



6176    int8_T* result;



6177} DataQueryInfo;



6178



6179#define _ssIsPositiveDataValue(S, inData, inDtId, inResult)                    \



6180    {                                                                          \



6181        DataQueryInfo info;                                                    \



6182        info.data = (inData);                                                  \



6183        info.dtId = (inDtId);                                                  \



6184        info.result = (inResult);                                              \



6185        _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)(S, GEN_FCN_IS_POSITIVE_DATA_VALUE, 0,  \



6186                                        &info) _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd;     \



6187    }



6188



6189#define _ssSignDataValue(S, inData, inDtId, inResult)                          \



6190    {                                                                          \



6191        DataQueryInfo info;                                                    \



6192        info.data = (inData);                                                  \



6193        info.dtId = (inDtId);                                                  \



6194        info.result = (inResult);                                              \



6195        _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)(S, GEN_FCN_SIGN_DATA_VALUE, 0, &info)  \



6196            _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd;                                        \



6197    }

6567/*  ssCallConvertBuiltInDType



6568 *  Options:



6569 *      satOnIntOverFlow:



6570 *          If true, saturate.  If false, the conversion is undefined when



6571 *          values are out of range (platform dependent conversion).



6572 *      doDiff:



6573 *          If true, compare original values and converted values and return



6574 *          true if they are different (e.g., value was saturated, etc).  If



6575 *          doDiff is false, this function always returns true.



6576 */



6577#if SS_SIM



6578#define ssCallConvertBuiltInDType(S,nVals,satOnIntOverFlow,doDiff,dt1,v1,dt2,v2)  \



6579    (S)->states.modelMethods2->ConvertBuiltInDType(nVals,satOnIntOverFlow,doDiff, \



6580        dt1,v1,dt2,v2)



6581#else



6582# define ssCallConvertBuiltInDType(S,nVals,satOnIntOverFlow,doDiff,dt1,v1,dt2,v2)  \



6583    ssCallConvertBuiltInDType_cannot_be_used_in_RTW



6584#endif

7887    _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd; \
